width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wenin>Wenin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 817<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/19/02 9:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=293.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.aradcliff.net/images/130.gif width=128 height=80></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Trent Lott</span><hr size=1> JC Watts didn't say anything negative, (was actually more supportive at first) until a couple days ago.  We're talking about the start of it all.  The problem that Republicans are having with the situation is not really what Lott said, but how it's affecting his leadership.  I'm more interested in knowing who is applying the pressure to see the comments as negative.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
If it had been a democrat to start this, Lott would not be in any trouble as majority leader. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
How is that?<br>
<br>
- Someone stirs the pot, questioning the remarks made by Lott.  Places a spin on them to accuse them of being racist remarks.<br>
<br>
- Media takes a hold of the story, since it is rather juicy.  &quot;Racist Republican leader&quot;<br>
<br>
- Faced with accusations of racist remarks, Lott is left to defend his statements.  He can't let the accusations just subside, since we are talking about public opinion and votes here.<br>
<br>
- He says that he was refering to Thurmond's stance of defense issues.<br>
<br>
- Media counters with pulling up his voting record, further showing that Lott could be a currently practicing racist.<br>
<br>
- Republican party members have a few stances they take.<br>
--- His remarks weren't racist.<br>
--- Lott can't lead the Senate since he is to busy defending his remarks.<br>
--- Lott's situation has reawakened the racist stigma of the Republican Party.  Republicans want to bury that, since it hampers their attempts to gain ground in the black community.  So if they remove Lott, it shows a change in the party.<br>
<br>
The Democrats have far more to gain from this than Republicans.  The Republicans are on top, a shake up does nothing but hurt them. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6094" target="top">Wenin Huirunda</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
&quot;You can believe whatever you wish. Just realize that you are wrong. Even if you don't realize it you are still wrong. The end.&quot; - Wise Man</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=radgen>Radgen</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 434<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/19/02 10:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=293.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/Radgen5.jpg height=150 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Trent Lott</span><hr size=1> Wenin what Lott said WAS raciest.  He may not meant what he said, and I highly doubt that he did, but again but that does not change the direct implication of what he said, intentional or not.<br>
<br>
He said that if Strom Thurmond, (who was running on ONE issue, protecting segregation), had won the White house, we would have not had all these problems we had today.  That isn't spin, that is the most direct interpretation of what he said.   I think part of the reason why this has lingered might be because everyone, supporter and detractors alike cannot fathom how Lott made such a huge verbal blunder.  Add in the discovery of past similar statements and THERE you have a mountain grown out of a molehill.  His voteing record does not come much into play, (though voteing against the MLK holiday looks bad, even Thurmond voted for that) because it is no different than any other conservative senator.<br>
<br>
This is not a small thing Lott did.  As leader of the GOP in the Senate, he has to be well aware of the GOP's less than stellar reputation amoung minorities, deserved or not.  He should have known the impact such a statement would have.  He is not some newbie. <br>
<br>
Lott saying that he was just trying to praise Thurmond.  Now THAT is spin.  <br>
<br>
I beg to differ on JC Watts, he was less than happy about this early last week and supportative is not what I would describe him as(of course that was before Lotts apology I believe, so he may have softened after that, as did many democrats.).  In fact he was on with a liberal talk show host who was defending Lott.<br>
<br>
You show me where it was a democrat who first complained about his remarks and then you might have an argument.  Like I said, I could not pinpoint WHO really made an outcry first.  It appears to have independently came from a handful of people who were at the party covering a wide spectrum of political ideology.  The press was REALLY slow to pick up on it, and really did not start to smell blood till much later than nis normal.<br>
<br>
Dems are certainly trying to take advantage of the situation, they would be foolish not to.  But I think on the otherside of the coin, Lott opened himself up to internal GOP enemies and they are maneuvering to take advantage.  I don't think any one factor can be really blamed alone for how this story exploded.  And do not forget, if Lott had not fed himself a his own foot, he would not be in this mess.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>edit:  I found the name of the University Lott made similar statements at in 1980.  It was Bob Jones University.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
