<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If the rest of the country had followed our lead(in voting for a hardline segregationist), we wouldn’t have had all these defense problems over all these years, either.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  <br>
<br>
Now how voteing for a (at the time) avowed raciest running on an extremely narrow protest platform has any relation to national defense, I have no clue, maybe you can tell me.  And you actually hit on what offends most people about the statement.  It implies that voteing for a man who's only purpose(at the time) was to keep Jim Crow fully entrenched somehow would have avoided all those problems you listed.  That IS a racial issue  <br>
<br>
Now don't get me wrong, I don't think Lott is raciest, I think what he said was.  It wasn't intentional.  The problem here is it took him till apology 3 or 4 just to say that instead of trying to simply spin what he said.<br>
<br>
There is also the issue of his saying almost exactly the same thing in a speech in 1980 at Bob Jones University, which has been accused of harboring raciest policies and teachings.  (The ban on inter-racial dateing being the most well known).<br>
<br>
This may have been one of those nod and wink statements that politicians from BOTH parties have been know to use, to curry favor with some of thier less than racially tolerant supporters.  Simply put I think Lott forgot what audience he was speaking to at the time.<br>
<br>
This is a press driven story now, but that is not how it started.  And I think I mispoke before.  There are two issues here.  There is the general political fallout from saying something stupid.  Lott is not the first and certainly not the last.  Whoever he faces in 2007, has already got a juicy issue to hit him over the head with, that is the general price he has to pay.  This was the original <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>small</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> story, the one that appeared and then started to fade.  On this facet of the issue I will agree that the Democrats took the lead.  <br>
<br>
On his position as majority leader however,  this was very slow coming.  I think several factors led to it though.   Most were internal to the GOP and a few external media voices, both liberal and conservative.  The press did not really get reinterested in this issue (and press interest HAD waned for a day or two after the intitial splash) until there were indications that there might be a move afoot to dethrone Lott over this.   The President chiming in and lambasteing Lott's statement also gave the story far more momentum than it otherwise would have(and I do give credit to Bush on this, he didn't have to say anything, or even be so harsh JUST to distance himself from those statements).  At this point the story has a life of its own.  You can't fault the press for following it (maybe for over hyping it a bit, but they do that with every story) but they did not create it.  This facet of the issue I do think is sourced from the backrooms of the GOP.<br>
<br>
If there had been no critism from the right on this statement, Lott would not be fighting to keep his position.  The political parties have very little influence on eachother when it comes to internal legislative positions.  This is not the first time that Democrats have called on a GOP congressional leader to step down over some political flap, it is almost expected.   I think you give them too much credit if you think THEY are driveing Lott out.<br>
<br>
<br>
