<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I don't think Lott is raciest, I think what he said was. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Ok which is it?  Lott has repeated said that he'd have liked Thurmond as a President when he ran (Note: he's never said he wanted him as President for Segregation reasons AFAIK).  You believe his statements are &quot;racist&quot;, and are generated by an apparent core belief.  How does this not make him a racist in your eyes?  What redeeming quality do you see Lott having, that makes him not be a racist?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
If there had been no critism from the right on this statement, Lott would not be fighting to keep his position. The political parties have very little influence on eachother when it comes to internal legislative positions. This is not the first time that Democrats have called on a GOP congressional leader to step down over some political flap, it is almost expected. I think you give them too much credit if you think THEY are driveing Lott out.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
- The Republicans HAD to respond, HAD to distance themselves from Lott's statements.<br>
- True, opposing political parties don't have <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>direct</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> influence on internal legisation of a party, but what they do have great influence over is creating situations in which the opposing political party <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>must</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> react to.  This is done all the time, by both sides.<br>
- True, it is expected for Democrats and Republicans alike to makes calls for their opposition leaders to step down when situations come up.<br>
- It is also <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>expected</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that both parties drum up assumptions and implications that place those political leaders in hot water.  Does our expectations of them, make this right?  No, mainly cause I have such low expectations of them both, when it comes to the backbiting name calling bullshit.<br>
<br>
The way I see it, the Dems or the Media got the boulder rolling down hill.  Republicans, like gravity took over.  Who's to blame for the boulder hitting some house at the bottom?<br>
<br>
I see the Republicans as gravity, since they had no other recourse in this situation.  They couldn't stand by and support Lott, since the media has continued to make accusations towards him.  Such support would have not calmed the waters, it would have stirred them to a higher cresendo.  So with no other recourse, the Republicans just did what they had to. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6094" target="top">Wenin Huirunda</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
